    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-07-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-07-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="353"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d353">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.512/1053</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Consul at Swatow</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Berger</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="17" xml:id="d353fn17">Copy transmitted to the Department by
                        the Minister in China in his despatch No. 363, July 31, 1930; received
                        September 10.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-07-31">July 31,
                            1930</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Legation has received your despatch of June
                    20, 1930,<note n="18" xml:id="d353fn18">Not printed.</note> inquiring whether
                    you might correctly protest against taxation in cases where there is no
                    discrimination against American goods.</p>
                <p>Provided that none of the commodities taxed have paid transit dues in lieu of
                    likin, and provided there is no discrimination against American goods, you
                    should refrain from any protest against the taxation mentioned. The Department
                    has held that, by accepting transit dues and issuing a transit pass which
                    purports to free the goods covered from all inland taxation en route, the
                    Chinese Government has entered into a contract and that attempts to levy likin
                    and inland taxes on goods covered by transit pass may properly be protested
                    against.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>For the Minister:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Mahlon F. Perkins</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Counselor of Legation</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
